Simple linear regression

sim_df = 
    tibble(
      x = rnorm(30, mean = 1, sd = 1),
      y = 2+ 3* x + rnorm(30, 0, 1)
    )
sim_df |> 
  ggplot(aes(x=x,y=y))+
  geom_point()

slr_fit = lm(y~x, data=sim_df)
coef(slr_fit)
## (Intercept)           x 
##    2.282127    2.933793

Turn this into a function

sim_regression = function(n_subj, beta_0 = 2, beta_1 = 3) {
  
  sim_df = 
    tibble(
      x = rnorm(n_subj, mean = 1, sd = 1),
      y = beta_0 + beta_1 * x + rnorm(n_subj, 0, 1)
    )

  slr_fit = lm(y~x, data=sim_df)
  tibble(
    beta0_hat = coef(slr_fit)[1],
    beta1_hat = coef(slr_fit)[2]
  )
}
sim_regression(n_subj = 30)
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   beta0_hat beta1_hat
##       <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1      2.41      2.83

One more example: birthday problem

birthdays = sample(1:365, 5, replace = TRUE) #data generating mechanism

repeated_bday = length(unique(birthdays)) < 5 #checking if have same birthday
repeated_bday
## [1] FALSE
bday_sim = function(n_room){
  birthdays = sample(1:365, n_room, replace=TRUE)
  repeated_bday = length(unique(birthdays)) < n_room
  repeated_bday
}

bday_sim(20)
## [1] TRUE
bday_sim_results = 
  expand_grid(
    bdays = 5:50,
    iter = 1:2500
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    result = map_lgl(bdays, bday_sim) #returns logical vector
  ) |> 
  group_by(
    bdays
  ) |> 
  summarize(
    prob_repeat=mean(result)
  )
